A technique used to identify specific molecules in different kinds of tissue. The tissue is treated with antibodies that bind the specific molecule. These are made visible under a microscope by using a color reaction, a radioisotope, colloidal gold, or a fluorescent dye. Immunohistochemistry is used to help diagnose diseases, such as cancer, and to detect the presence of microorganisms. It is also used in basic research to understand how cells grow and differentiate (become more specialized).

Immunohistochemical staining techniques allow for the visualization of antigens via the sequential application of a specific antibody to the antigen (primary antibody), a secondary antibody to the primary antibody and an enzyme complex with a chromogenic substrate. The enzymatic activation of the chromogen results in a visible reaction product at the antigen site. The specimen may then be counterstained and coverslipped. Results are interpreted using a light microscope and aid in the differential diagnosis of pathophysiological processes, which may or may not be associated with a particular antigen.

_source.description: This clinical trial studies single photon emission computed tomography/computed tomography (SPECT/CT) in determining dosimetry in patients with non-Hodgkin lymphoma receiving radioimmunotherapy. Dosimetry is the measurement of radiation exposure from different types of radiation used in the treatment or detection of diseases, including cancer. Diagnostic procedures, such as SPECT/CT, may help determine how much of the radiation is absorbed by tumor tissue and bone marrow and may help doctors determine how much radioimmunotherapy to administer to each patient to get optimal results.

eligibility_criteria.description: Clinically stable patients undergoing I-131 tositumomab (Bexxar) or Y-90 ibritumomab tiuxetan (Zevalin) for treatment of non-Hodgkin lymphoma
Patients with a blood creatinine level > 2.0 mg/dl within a month of this procedure
Taking metformin (example: Glucophage, Glucovance, Avandamet, Metaglip)
Diabetic patients with a blood creatinine level > 1.5 mg/dl within a month of this procedure
Patients who are unable to lie flat on the imaging systems long enough to permit imaging protocols to be performed

Medical condition
* Renal transplant
* Active or ongoing kidney disease or kidney failure, including but not limited to: functioning renal transplant, solitary kidney, proteinuria, multiple myeloma, acute and chronic nephropathies
* Myasthenia gravis
* Thyroid cancer or overactive thyroid
* Severe congestive heart failure
IF CT CONTRAST AGENTS ARE TO BE USED:
Chest pain, angina, or heart failure

outcome_measures.analysis_method: Univariate regression models will be used to assess the marginal relation between tumor response and the individual dosimetric and biologic parameters. Will calculate metrics summarizing the predictive or discriminatory ability of the logistic regression model. For tumor level models will calculate the correlation between tumor shrinkage (or standardized uptake value) and the linear predictor from a regression model. Univariate analysis will be used to assess the correlation between toxicity (or fractional decrease in blood count parameters) and the various variables.
outcome_measures.measure: Regression analysis to identify key factors and to develop predictive model
outcome_measures.time_frame: Up to 10 days after therapy injection

outcome_measures.measure: Positron emission tomography (PET) metabolic response assessed using International Workshop Criteria and PET Response Criteria in Solid Tumors

outcome_measures.analysis_method: Will be determined coupling patient SPECT/CT imaging with the patient specific 3-dimensional (3D) tumor dosimetry methodologies developed previously.
outcome_measures.time_frame: Up to 10 days after therapy injection

outcome_measures.analysis_method: Will be determined coupling patient SPECT/CT imaging with the patient specific 3D tumor dosimetry methodologies developed previously.
outcome_measures.time_frame: Up to 10 days after therapy injection

outcome_measures.measure: Incidence of myelotoxicity assessed using Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events criteria

outcome_measures.analysis_method: Assessed using molecular markers in tumor biopsy specimens, detected by immunohistochemical analysis and molecular tests. Percentage of cells staining positive for select biomarkers will be determined and the intensity will be graded as low, intermediate or strong. Sensitivity to the cold antibody will be estimated based on the apoptotic potential and/or on cell clearance model fits to changes in CT defined tumor volumes. Will measure the plasma concentration of fms-related tyrosine kinase 3 ligand by quantitative sandwich enzyme immunoassay.
outcome_measures.time_frame: Up to day of scan 3 or 4

outcome_measures.analysis_method: Will be determined coupling patient SPECT/CT imaging with the patient specific 3D tumor dosimetry methodologies developed previously.
outcome_measures.time_frame: Up to 10 days after therapy injection

outcome_measures.analysis_method: Will be determined coupling patient SPECT/CT imaging with the patient specific 3D tumor dosimetry methodologies developed previously.
outcome_measures.time_frame: Up to 10 days after therapy injection

outcome_measures.analysis_method: Bone marrow dose maps for selected marrow rich-regions will be computed with a modified version of the DPM Monte Carlo program. Patient SPECT/CT imaging data will be coupled with a map of the marrow composition determined by the dual-energy quantitative CT method. Conventional ‘blood-based’ dose estimates will be determined from peripheral blood samples using standard techniques. For comparison both imaging based and blood based results will be used in the predictive model. For bone marrow, the correlation between tracer predicted and therapy delivered absorbed dose will be determined.
outcome_measures.time_frame: Up to 10 days after therapy injection

_source.public_title: SPECT/CT in Determining Dosimetry in Patients with Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma Receiving Radioimmunotherapy
_source.scientific_description:
PRIMARY OBJECTIVES:
I. To develop imaging based methods for accurate bone marrow dosimetry.
II. To develop predictive models for tumor response and bone marrow toxicity incorporating key dosimetric factors as well as biologic factors such as differential proliferation and radiosensitivity determined by biomarkers.

OUTLINE:
Patients undergo SPECT/CT scans over 30 minutes for up to 6 scans.
_source.title: Imaging Based Dosimetry for Individualized Internal Emitter Therapy
